721277f-a.text:
Madison Avenue, south from East 37th Street. At the left margin is the old J. P. Morgan residence. This was demolished for the present Library. Beyond are two brown stone houses that were subsequently replaced by an apartment building. The two story garage, the Tudoric "Percy Silver' residence, and the Church of the Incarnation remain. The row below, adjoining the dominant Cameron Building were replaced (in 1939) by the 14 story Goodhue House. Onposite same is the marble B. Altman Lepartment Store. Gutlined against the lower part of this building is a row of residences that were removed for the dom'ustion Engineering Building. Closer to the camera is a more individual row. lans for an apartment house here were sdvnnced in June of 1940. 721281f-a.text:
Madison Avenue, east side, from 38th to 37th Streets, showing the Fraternity Clubs Building, 22 East 38th Street, built by the Allerton House interests about 1923, on the lot formerly occupied by South Church (Dutch Reformed). In the middle of the block is the Hotel Duane, about contemporary with it, occupying the site of 237-239 Madison Avenue, the two old four-story houses which used to stand there. On the N.E. corner of 37th Street is the old Delmar Mansion, which has been occupied since 1923 by the National
Democratic Club.
